---
import ToolPage from '../layouts/ToolPage.astro';
import JsonTool from '../components/JsonTool.tsx';
import LandingLinks from '../components/LandingLinks.astro';
---

<ToolPage
  title="JSON Formatter & Validator — Free Online"
  description="Format, validate and minify JSON online for free. Paste your JSON to beautify it with syntax highlighting, get instant error locations, or minify in one click. Runs in your browser."
  h1="JSON Formatter & Validator"
  intro="Paste JSON on the left and get clean, indented output with syntax highlighting on the right. Invalid JSON is flagged instantly with the exact line and column, and you can minify or download the result — everything stays in your browser."
  path="/json"
  faq={[
    {
      q: 'Is my JSON uploaded anywhere?',
      a: 'No. Parsing, formatting and validation all happen locally in your browser — nothing is sent to a server.',
    },
    {
      q: 'How does it show where my JSON is invalid?',
      a: 'When JSON fails to parse, the tool reports the error message along with the line and column where the problem was detected, so you can jump straight to it.',
    },
    {
      q: 'Can I minify JSON as well as beautify it?',
      a: 'Yes. Switch to Minify to strip all whitespace into a single compact line, or use Beautify with 2 spaces, 4 spaces or tabs.',
    },
    {
      q: 'Does it accept JSON with comments or trailing commas?',
      a: 'No. It validates strict JSON, so comments, trailing commas, single-quoted strings and unquoted property names are reported as errors.',
    },
  ]}
>
  <JsonTool client:only="react" />

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">What is a JSON formatter?</h2>
    <p class="mt-2">
      JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is the most common format for APIs, config files and data
      exchange. A JSON formatter takes raw or minified JSON and re-indents it into a clean, nested
      structure that is easy to read — while a validator checks that the syntax is correct and points
      out exactly where it breaks.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">How to use it</h2>
    <ol class="mt-2 list-decimal space-y-1 pl-6">
      <li>Paste or upload your JSON into the left panel.</li>
      <li>The formatted, syntax-highlighted result appears on the right instantly.</li>
      <li>Pick <strong>Beautify</strong> with your preferred indent, or <strong>Minify</strong> to compact it.</li>
      <li>Click <strong>Copy</strong> or <strong>Download</strong> to save the result.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Strict JSON rules the validator checks</h2>
    <p class="mt-2">
      Valid JSON requires double-quoted property names and strings, balanced brackets, and commas
      only between values. JavaScript conveniences such as comments, trailing commas,
      <code>undefined</code>, <code>NaN</code> and single-quoted strings are not valid JSON. Keeping
      validation strict helps catch payloads that may work in a permissive editor but fail in an API.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">How to use an error location</h2>
    <p class="mt-2">
      Start at the reported line and column, but also inspect the character immediately before it.
      Parsers often notice an error only when the next token becomes impossible. A message near a
      closing brace, for example, may be caused by a missing comma on the previous line or an
      unescaped quote earlier in the same string.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Beautify versus minify</h2>
    <p class="mt-2">
      Beautifying adds whitespace for humans and is best for debugging, review and version control.
      Minifying removes insignificant whitespace for compact storage or transport. Both operations
      preserve parsed values, but large integers and duplicate object keys deserve extra care because
      JavaScript parsing behavior may not preserve every source-level detail.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <h3 class="mt-4 font-semibold text-slate-800">Is my JSON uploaded anywhere?</h3>
    <p class="mt-1">
      No. Parsing, formatting and validation all happen locally in your browser — nothing is sent to
      a server.
    </p>
    <h3 class="mt-4 font-semibold text-slate-800">How does it show where my JSON is invalid?</h3>
    <p class="mt-1">
      When JSON fails to parse, the tool reports the error message along with the line and column
      where the problem was detected, so you can jump straight to it.
    </p>
    <h3 class="mt-4 font-semibold text-slate-800">Can I minify JSON as well as beautify it?</h3>
    <p class="mt-1">
      Yes. Switch to Minify to strip all whitespace into a single compact line, or use Beautify with
      2 spaces, 4 spaces or tabs.
    </p>
    <h3 class="mt-4 font-semibold text-slate-800">Does it accept JSON with comments or trailing commas?</h3>
    <p class="mt-1">
      No. It validates strict JSON, so comments, trailing commas, single-quoted strings and unquoted
      property names are reported as errors.
    </p>

    <LandingLinks group="json" heading="More JSON tools" />
  </Fragment>
</ToolPage>
